content.description: Fun pocketed route.  Rating this a 5.6 to keep in line with the rest of the sandbagged ratings in the area.  The rock quality was surprisingly good and the summit is amazing.  I built a traditional anchor at the top, on the pinnacle to climbers left of where the route ends. However, you could belay from the top of WBTYM if you're not fiending for the summit views like I was.
content.protection: I used all cams, and the route went entirely on gear - placement was tricky but confidence inspiring.  We used the WBTYM anchors to rappel.
content.location: Start same as Wham Bam Thank You Ma'am, and when you get to a small bulge, go climber's left instead of right.  See picture for route I took, which was the path of least resistance.

content.description: The obvious hand crack below the chimney is likely the crux. Pro is sparse in the main chimney, but the climb gets easier with height. At the upper chockstones, move left, up juggy face to summit.
content.protection: Single rack of cams. Shares two bolt belay/rap of Northwest routes or one may hurdle gap to access the WBTYM anchors.
content.location: Farthest right (NE) route of the southeast wall, which starts near a tall Saguaro.

content.description: As I climbed this route I thought it felt like another hard 5.9 only to find out the rating is a 5.7.  I have succumbed to the fact that in the Superstitions I have no idea how to climb, rate, judge anything over a 5.5.....   Bottom of the route is junky and loose, middle section is decent, top of formation junky and loose.
content.protection: I placed all ranges of cams up to #4 since I like to pretend I'm safe when climbing on exfoliating rock.  Old anchors at the top that allow a quick rappel off the west side.
content.location: Route can be located by obvious chimney that sort of narrows and has two chockstones midway.
